# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arthur-b-guise-medal
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Manual fire suppression includes the use of a fire blanket, fire extinguisher, or a standpipe system.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] A fire blanket is a sheet of fire retardant material that is designed to be placed over a fire to smother it out.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Small fire blankets are meant for inception stage fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] They are normally made of fiberglass or Kevlar.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Larger ones can be found in laboratories and factories, and are designed to be wrapped around a person whose clothes have caught fire.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are devices that contain and discharge a substance that extinguishes or puts out a fire.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These handheld devices come in a huge range of sizes, but the most common are portable fire extinguishers, typically weighing up to 15 kg in total.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These can be easily handled and operated by one person and placement can either be wall-mounted, on a fire extinguisher trolley or housed inside a cabinet.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers are one of the most common manual fire suppression devices and are required in all commercial buildings and vehicles.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Fire extinguishers can be used with little to no training and are meant for small incipient stage fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] The most common extinguisher is the ABC extinguisher and are found in most offices and homes.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] It can be used on normal fires, liquid fires, and electrical fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] There are also special extinguishers for kitchen fires and for use on burning metals, those being Class K and Class D respectively.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Standpipes are installed in most large, multistory buildings.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] There are two types of standpipes: dry and wet.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Most standpipes are dry systems and cannot be used by the public.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Dry systems require a fire engine to pump water into the system.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Most dry systems do not have pre-connected hoses and require firefighters to bring in the hose.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] In wet systems, there is always water in the pipes and they can be used by anyone.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Wet systems will have hoses so building occupants can try and extinguish fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Wet systems are becoming less common with the increase in number of sprinkler systems being installed.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] In some systems, firefighters have the option of pumping a Fire Department Connection (FDC) which will increase the water pressure at a standpipe in the event of a fire pump failure or loss of pressure.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Typically, these systems pressurize the sprinkler system or the standpipe but not both at the same time.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Automatic control means are any form of suppression that requires no human intervention these can include a fire sprinkler system, a gaseous clean agent, or automatic foam suppression system.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Most automatic suppression systems would be found in large commercial kitchens or other high-risk areas.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Fire sprinkler systems are installed in all types of buildings, commercial and residential.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] They are usually located at ceiling level and are connected to a reliable water source, most commonly municipal water supply.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] A typical automatic sprinkler system operates when heat at the site of a fire causes a fusible link or glass component in the sprinkler head to fail, thereby releasing the water from the sprinkler head.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] This means that only the sprinkler heads at the fire location actuate – not all the sprinklers on a floor or in a building.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] However, certain systems, such as deluge systems, do spray water from all heads in the same zone upon actuation.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Sprinkler systems help to reduce the growth of a fire, thereby increasing life safety and limiting structural damage.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Gaseous clean agents are installed to result in less fire and water damage than sprinklers, such as in computer rooms.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] The system works by flooding an area with a gas which interferes with the fire tetrahedron.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These systems are often found in areas where people are not going to be present when the system is activated such as datacenters, cooling systems, and other industrial applications.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Activating a gaseous clean agent system when people are present can cause injury or death, and are usually equipped with an audible notification system to warn any potential occupants to evacuate the area.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Automatic foam suppression systems come in three main forms low expansion, medium expansion, and high expansion.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam expands less than 20 times its original size.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These systems can be installed in a variety of places but are commonly found in places where hydrocarbons are stored.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Low expansion foam systems when using film forming work by making a blanket of foam over the burning liquid to both cool it down and suppress the vapors.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Medium expansion foam expands between 20 and 200 times its original size.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These can be installed in outdoor settings like transfer stations or for use in open pits.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Medium foam is used outdoors because it is denser than high expansion and will not blow away as easily.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] It works by covering what is on fire in a thick blanket of foam to smother it and suppress vapors.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] High expansion foam expands between 200 and 1000 times its original size.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These systems are commonly installed in large volume areas like airplane hangars, mine shafts, and ship holds.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These systems are normally installed inside and make a very light foam.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] They extinguish the fire by rapid smothering and cooling.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Its rapid rate of expansion enables it to fill large areas with foam rapidly.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] When used on LNG tanks they provide an added insulation layer that helps reduce the vapor rate.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Nozzles that are powered by electrical energy that is generated and supplied by fire detection and control devices and are typically closed.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] ILDFA uses a dual approach, combining a water-based fire suppression system in conjunction with a hollow, perforated flooring system to drain and remove spilled flammable liquid.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] This approach reduces the risk of pool fires inside infrastructure by diverting any leaked fuel away from potential ignition sources or by extinguishing any flammable liquid fire by depriving it of oxygen once it is removed.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Fire detection works using smoke or heat sensors.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These systems are very effective tool at alerting people in the immediate vicinity of where the fire is detected but building regulations require an integrated fire detection system.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] These system not only alerts people throughout the building by triggering the fire alarm but it can also summon emergency services.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] There are two types of systems available – addressable and conventional.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Addressable systems monitor the specific location of each device (e.g. smoke detector, call point or sounder).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] It means in the event of a fire or other emergency you know exactly where the problem is.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] This saves precious time and helps the emergency services prevent the loss of life and serious damage.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Conventional systems can only determine the problem is in a general area and thus are more suited for small sites.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] When the fire detection system is activated it can also send an alert to the local fire department, broadcast a prerecorded warning message and unlock the buildings access control system.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Hypoxic air fire prevention systems, also known as oxygen reduction systems are new automatic fire prevention systems that permanently reduce the oxygen concentration inside the protected volumes so that ignition or fire spreading cannot occur.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] Unlike traditional fire suppression systems that usually extinguish fire after it is detected, hypoxic air is able to prevent fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] At lower altitudes hypoxic air is safe to breathe for healthy individuals.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] All AFP systems are required to be installed and maintained in accordance with strict guidelines in order to maintain compliance with the local building code and the fire code.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/active-fire-protection] AFP works alongside modern architectural designs and construction materials and fire safety education to prevent, retard, and suppress structural fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] Simeoni read physics at the University of Corsica, graduating with a *Licence* (BSc) in 1994.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] He completed an MEng in thermal transfers at Polytech Marseille in 1996 before returning to Corsica for doctoral work.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] His PhD thesis (2000) developed multiphase models to improve predictions of forest-fire spread.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] After earning his doctorate, Simeoni was appointed *maître de conférences* (assistant professor) at the University of Corsica, where he led a CNRS-affiliated research group on forest-fire modelling.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] In 2013, he moved to the United Kingdom to take up the BRE Chair of Fire Safety Engineering at the University of Edinburgh, a post he held until 2015.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] Simeoni joined WPI in 2017 and became department head the same year.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] Beyond the university sector, he serves as treasurer (board member since 2014) of the International Association of Wildland Fire (IAWF).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] Simeoni’s work combines laboratory and field experiments with computational fluid-dynamics models to examine flame spread, firebrand generation and coupled fire–atmosphere interactions.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/albert-simeoni] His recent projects include establishing a National Science Foundation Wildfire Interdisciplinary Research Center at WPI, and developing physics-based tools for assessing extreme fire behaviour.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] An **area of refuge** or **safe room** is a place in a building designed to hold occupants during a fire or other emergency when evacuation may not be safe or possible.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] Occupants can wait there until rescued or relieved by firefighters.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] In some instances, an area of refuge or refuge area may refer to a designated space in a multi-unit residential building that can provide relief from unsafe or uncomfortable conditions in individual units.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] An area of refuge is typically supplied with a steady supply of fresh or filtered outside air.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] A two way communication system is provided on each floor above or below the main floor.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] A call box is required in each area of refuge, which can call into a central location called a base station.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] If the station is not attended 24 hours a day, the call must automatically call to an outside location and have two-way voice person to person communication capabilities.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] Such locations are usually required to be bounded by fire-resistant walls and floors.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/area-of-refuge] In the context of climate change, where older buildings may not be designed for changing climate conditions, refuge spaces are sometimes discussed in terms of providing communal areas in multi-unit buildings for when temperature and air quality is not safe or comfortable in individual units.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/arthur-b-guise-medal] Guise Medal** was established in 1983 and has been awarded annually starting in 1985 by the Society of Fire Protection Engineers.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/arthur-b-guise-medal] Named in memory of Arthur Guise, an engineer who developed dry chemicals as fire extinguishing agents, it recognizes eminent achievement in the advancement of the science and technology of fire protection engineering.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Today there are numerous types of automatic fire suppression systems and standards for each one.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Systems are as diverse as the many applications.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In general, however, automatic fire suppression systems fall into two categories: *engineered* and *pre-engineered* systems.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] By definition, an automatic fire suppression system can operate without human intervention.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] To do so it must possess a means of detection, actuation and delivery.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In many systems, detection is accomplished by mechanical or electrical means.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Mechanical detection uses fusible-link or thermo-bulb detectors.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] These detectors are designed to separate at a specific temperature and release tension on a release mechanism.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Electrical detection uses heat detectors equipped with self-restoring, normally-open contacts which close when a predetermined temperature is reached.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Remote and local manual operation is also possible.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Actuation usually involves either a pressurized fluid and a release valve, or in some cases an electric pump.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Delivery is accomplished by means of piping and nozzles.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Nozzle design is specific to the agent used and coverage desired.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Water is the most prevalent fire suppression agent in use worldwide.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] However, the use of water does have some limitations, which can range from inadequate supplies (particularly in less developed regions) to operations and processes which are highly susceptible to water damage.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In some cases, certain contents or processes (such as water-reactive chemicals or metals, molten materials, etc.) are truly incompatible with water; water discharge could lead to explosion.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Despite their effectiveness, chemical fire extinguishing agents are not without disadvantages.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In the early 20th century, carbon tetrachloride was extensively used as a dry cleaning solvent, a refrigerant and as a fire extinguishing agent.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In time, it was found carbon tetrachloride could lead to severe health effects.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] From the mid-1960s Halon 1301 was the industry standard for protecting high-value assets from the threat of fire.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301 had many benefits as a fire suppression agent; it is fast-acting, safe for assets and required minimal storage space.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Halon 1301's major drawbacks are that it depletes atmospheric ozone and is potentially harmful to humans.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Since 1987, some 191 nations have signed The Montreal Protocol on Substances That Deplete the Ozone Layer.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] The Protocol is an international treaty designed to protect the ozone layer by phasing out the production of a number of substances believed to be responsible for ozone depletion.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Among these were halogenated hydrocarbons often used in fire suppression.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] As a result, manufacturers have focused on alternatives to Halon 1301 and Halon 1211 (halogenated hydrocarbons).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] A number of countries have also taken steps to mandate the removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Most notably these include Germany and Australia, the first two countries in the world to require this action.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In both of these countries complete removal of installed Halon systems has been completed except for a very few essential-use applications.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] The European Union is currently undergoing a similar mandated removal of installed Halon systems.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire extinguisher patent was issued to Alanson Crane of Virginia on Feb.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] The first fire sprinkler system was patented by H.W.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] But the first practical automatic sprinkler system was invented in 1874 by Henry S.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] He installed the system in a piano factory he owned.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Since the early 1990s manufacturers have successfully developed safe and effective Halon alternatives.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] These include DuPont's FM-200, American Pacific's Halotron, FirePro's FPC Compound, Plumis’ Automist and 3M's Novec 1230 Fire Protection Fluid.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Generally, the Halon replacement agents available today fall into two broad categories, in-kind (gaseous extinguishing agents) or not in-kind (alternative technologies).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] In-kind gaseous agents generally fall into two further categories, halocarbons and inert gases.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/automatic-fire-suppression] Not in-kind alternatives include such options as water mist or the use of early warning smoke detection systems.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] Merci earned an MSc in electro-mechanical engineering from Ghent University in 1997 and completed his PhD in 2000 on the modelling of turbulent non-premixed flames.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] After completing a postdoctoral fellowship with the Research Foundation – Flanders (FWO), he expanded his research into fire safety and established the "Fire Safety Science and Engineering" research unit at Ghent University.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] Merci has held a 10% guest professorship at KU Leuven since 2015.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] He was Otto Monsted Guest Professor at the Technical University of Denmark in 2016 and has served as a guest professor at the University of Science and Technology of China since 2022.
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] Since 2015, he has been Editor-in-Chief of *Fire Safety Journal* and is involved in managing the International Master of Science in Fire Safety Engineering (IMFSE).
[src:arthur-b-guise-medal/bart-merci] He has supervised over 20 completed PhD dissertations and 150 master's theses.
